\begin_layout Subsection
HACC
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:HACC"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the HACC simulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hacc_2014"

\end_inset

 in this work; HACC uses a hybrid parallel algorithmic structure, splitting
 the force calculation into a specially designed grid-based long/medium
 range spectral particle mesh (PM) component and a short-range solver, which
 uses direct particle-particle interactions, i.e., a P
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

M algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1988csup.book.....H"

\end_inset

.
 The simulation uses 
\begin_inset Formula $300$
\end_inset

 long time steps and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 subcycles.
 Note that one long time step corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta a\sim0.003$
\end_inset

.
 The choice of time steps is determined after several convergence tests
 such that the simulation reproduces an accurate halo mass functions as
 well as the clustering compared to full N-body simulations.
 Quantitatively, the simulations recover the halo masses to 98% fidelity
 and better than 
\begin_inset Formula $1\%$
\end_inset

 agreement of the power spectra on 
\begin_inset Formula $k<1h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
 Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2015arXiv151006665S"

\end_inset

 shows the details of those convergence tests.
 The simulation assumes a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

CDM cosmology with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{m}=0.2648$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{\Lambda}=0.7352$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{b}h^{2}=0.02258$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{s}=0.963$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{8}=0.8$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h=0.71$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $4096^{3}$
\end_inset

 particles with mass resolution 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{p}\sim5\times10^{9}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 in a 
\begin_inset Formula $4h^{-1}{\rm Gpc}$
\end_inset

 box giving a particle mass of about 
\begin_inset Formula $5.3\times10^{10}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 Dark matter halos are identified using the friends-of-friends (FOF) algorithm
 with the linking length of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.168$
\end_inset

.
 All of the results we consider are at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.15$
\end_inset

.
 We have four realizations of the simulation, each with volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $64(h^{-1}{\rm Gpc})^{3}$
\end_inset

, and subdivide each of our realizations into 16 subvolumes of 
\begin_inset Formula $4(h^{-1}{\rm Gpc})^{3}$
\end_inset

 each, yielding 64 samples with which to estimate the covariance matrix
 for galaxy correlation functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Halo Occupation Distributions (HODs)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:hod"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
In order to test how galaxy biases affect the BAO measurement, we generate
 galaxy mock catalogs with various galaxy biases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
To populate halos with galaxies, we use the Halo Occupation Distribution
 (HOD) method (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2005ApJ...633..791Z,berlind02,berlind03,berlind_weinburg03,krause_etal13,peacock00a"

\end_inset

), w
\color inherit
hich assumes that the number of galaxies in a halo correlates with its halo
 mass.
 The HOD functional form (based on a number of free parameters, 5 in our
 case) provides probabilities for two types of galaxies: central and satellite
 galaxies.
 Central galaxies are the ones which exist at the center of the halo and
 often the most brightest galaxies in its halo, while satellite galaxies
 are the ones which exists around the central galaxies.
 A halo hosts a central galaxy with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle N_{cen}(M)\rangle$
\end_inset

 and a number of satellite galaxies given by a Poisson distribution with
 mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle N_{sat}(M)\rangle$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle N_{cen}(M)\rangle=\frac{1}{2}{\rm erfc}\left[\frac{{\rm ln}(M_{cut}/M)}{\sqrt{2}\sigma}\right],\label{eq:Ncen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle N_{sat}(M)\rangle=N_{cen}(M)\left(\frac{M-\kappa M_{cut}}{M_{1}}\right)^{\alpha},\label{eq:Nsat}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the halo mass, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{cut}$
\end_inset

 is the characteristic minimum mass of halos which can host the central
 galaxy with the probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the characteristic transition width, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 determines the minimum mass of halos for satellite galaxies, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 determines the fractional number of satellite galaxies.
 All those five parameters are free parameters.
 We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{sat}(M)$
\end_inset

 is zero when 
\begin_inset Formula $M<\kappa M_{cut}$
\end_inset

 and halos do not host satellite galaxies without a central galaxy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2005ApJ...633..791Z"

\end_inset

.
 The total number of galaxies hosted by each halo is a sum of the number
 of central and satellite galaxies.

\color black
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:weight_hod"

\end_inset

 illustrates 
\begin_inset Formula $<N_{cen}>$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $<N_{sat}>$
\end_inset

.
 E
\color inherit
quations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ncen"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Nsat"

\end_inset

 are not the only possible functional form for the HOD, but these forms
 are known to successfully reproduce the clustering of the BOSS galaxies
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2011ApJ...728..126W"

\end_inset

 and are therefore a convenient choice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After assigning a number of galaxies to each halo, we distribute those galaxies
 within the halo.
 The central galaxy is always at the center of the halo, while the distribution
 of satellite galaxies follows a spherically symmetric NFW profile specified
 by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho(r)=\frac{4\rho_{s}}{\frac{cr}{R_{{\rm vir}}}(1+\frac{cr}{R_{{\rm vir}}})^{2}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 is the virial radius for the halo, 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the concentration parameter, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the density at the characteristic scale 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{s}=R_{{\rm vir}}/c$
\end_inset

.
 We use the emulator described in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013ApJ...768..123K"

\end_inset

 to generate a table of concentration-mass relations for halos at each redshift.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We set the velocity of the central galaxy to be equal to the host halo velocity.
 We assume that satellite galaxies are randomly moving inside the host halos.
 Therefore, the velocities of the satellite galaxies are the sum of their
 host halo velocity and a random virial component.
 For this random component, we draw from a Gaussian distribution with zero
 mean and variance given by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle v_{x}^{2}\rangle=\langle v_{y}^{2}\rangle=\langle v_{z}^{2}\rangle=\frac{1}{3}\frac{GM}{R_{{\rm vir}}}.\label{eq:variance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There have been several discussions about velocity bias and how to assign/define
 the velocity for galaxies (e.g., using only inner 10% of particles to define
 velocities for central galaxies) (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2014MNRAS.444..476R"

\end_inset

).
 However, we expect that these velocities will only affect at scales smaller
 than 
