\begin_layout Subsection
Effects of Biased Tracers on BAO Peaks in Real-Space before Reconstruction
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:real-prerecon"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we investigate the effect of galaxy bias on the measurement
 of the BAO peak without reconstruction.
 We use the method described in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:fitting"

\end_inset

 to measure the shift of the BAO peak.
 The non-linear parameter in the template function (defined in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:model2"

\end_inset

) used for the analysis is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=7.5h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 for all the galaxy samples.
 Since the shifts due to galaxy bias and due to the deviation from the fiducial
 cosmology are indistinguishable, it is important to understand how much
 systematic biases are induced by galaxy biases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:alpha_prerecon"

\end_inset

 shows the measured shifts on the BAO scale as a function of galaxy bias.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 measured for the HOD samples are given in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:alphas"

\end_inset

.
 We detect the shift in the BAO scale (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim3\sigma$
\end_inset

 for most samples) but do not detect a strong variation with the galaxy
 bias.
 Indeed, the shift is consistent with being constant for biases 
\begin_inset Formula $<$
\end_inset

 2.0 and only increases for extremely large biases.
 These results agree with the trends shown in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2011ApJ...734...94M"

\end_inset

.
 The absolute values of shifts for our samples are larger than the shifts
 measured in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mehta2011"

\end_inset

.
 This is because we use the samples at a lower redshift.
 In fact, the size of the increase in shifts is roughly consistent with
 the expectations from perturbation theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2008PhRvD..77b3533C,2009PhRvD..80f3508P,2012PhRvD..85j3523S"

\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha-1$
\end_inset

 value is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{2}(z)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $D(z)$
\end_inset

 is the linear growth rate.
 However, we find that the bias dependence of our samples is weaker than
 what was predicted in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2009PhRvD..80f3508P"

\end_inset

.

\color black
 Note that we use different HOD models than the one used in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2009PhRvD..80f3508P"

\end_inset

, which give different higher-order biases in perturbation theory.
 Since the shift of the BAO peak is due to higher-order terms (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2012PhRvD..85j3523S,2009PhRvD..80f3508P"

\end_inset

), the reason we see the weaker dependence on biases is possibly due to
 different HOD models.
 
\end_layout

