\begin_layout Subsection
Smoothing Scales and Reconstruction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we explore the effects of various steps in the reconstruction
 method: smoothing scales and noise due to high-biased objects (and galaxy
 bias?).
 We first vary the smoothing scales used to estimate the linear density
 field.
 When the smoothing scale is smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{n}^{-1/3}$
\end_inset

, the reconstructed field is affected by noise due to the finite number
 of galaxies.
 On the other hand, using too large smoothing scale will degrade the robustness
 of the method.
 To test these effects, we use two galaxy samples 
\begin_inset Formula $HOD1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $HOD9$
\end_inset

, which have two extreme number densities.
 The number densities for these samples are 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-3}(h^{-1}{\rm Mpc})^{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $3.73\times10^{-5}(h^{-1}{\rm Mpc})^{3}$
\end_inset

, which correspond to the minimum smoothing scales of 
\begin_inset Formula $10h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $30h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the case of the 
\begin_inset Formula $HOD1$
\end_inset

 sample, we test the effect of large smoothing scales on the robustness
 of the method using the smoothing scales of 
\begin_inset Formula $10h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $20h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $30h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:hod1_smooth"

\end_inset

 shows the reconstructed correlation functions for these smoothing scales.
 For the case of the large smoothing scales, the BAO peaks are slightly
 degraded compared to the correlation function with the 
\begin_inset Formula $10h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 smoothing scale, but their peaks are still more sharpened than the case
 of pre-reconstruction.
 The measured shifts on the BAO peak with various smoothing scales are shown
 in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:hod1_smooth"

\end_inset

.
 As the smoothing scale becomes larger, the scatter on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values becomes large
\color black
r.
 This is because the correlation in the measured shifts for these samples
 becomes smaller.
 Quantitatively, the cross-correlation coefficients for the samples with
 
\begin_inset Formula $R=20h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $30h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the ones with 
\begin_inset Formula $R=10h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $0.71$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0.53$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 In addition to degrading the robustness of the reconstruction, we find
 that the reconstructed correlation function is slightly distorted on small
 scales by the increase of the smoothing scales.
\end_layout

