\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 fields using different samples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We conclude this chapter with the following summary of our findings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We find that the effect of shot noise is particularly large on high-biased
 objects, and therefore decide to use the samples generated from the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 HOD method, which removes the variance on the shift of the BAO peak due
 to randomly subsampling halos.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For the case of pre-reconstruction, we detect the shift in the BAO scale
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim3\sigma$
\end_inset

 for most samples), which is consistent with the expectations from perturbation
 theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2008PhRvD..77b3533C,2009PhRvD..80f3508P,2012PhRvD..85j3523S"

\end_inset

.
 The shift is consistent with being constant for biases 
\begin_inset Formula $<$
\end_inset

 2.0 and only increases for extremely large biases, as is seen in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mehta2011"

\end_inset

.
 However, we do not find the strong bias dependence predicted in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2009PhRvD..80f3508P"

